A group in Rivers state under the aegis of Rivers Peoples Alliance (RPA) has condemned plans by Nigerian Maritime Administration and Safety Agency (NIMASA) to deliver Covid-19 items to the University of Portharcourt Teaching Hospital instead of the Rivers State Government. Apparently miffed by the development, the group in a statement signed by its General Secretary, Pius Okechukwu and made available to newsmen yesterday, described the action as selective because Rivers state is being controlled by a perceived opposition party. The statement added that NIMASA should retrace its plan to handover materials to another body when there’s a democratically elected government in Rivers State. Recall that recently, the same agency delivered Covid-19 materials directly to the Lagos Government that coordinated the Lagos affairs, who then sent same to the LUTH. In the statement, the group also alleged that “our state government has been in the forefront to ensure that the scourge is contained.” It said, “Now that a federal government agency wants to distribute items, it choose to ignore the state government for obvious reasons and deal directly with the teaching hospital, against what it did in Lagos. “Coronavirus knows no colour or race, we demand an immediate explanation why Rivers should be treated differently from Lagos. “When it was the turn of Lagos it was express delivery via Lagos Government but now that it’s the turn of Rivers FG now remembers that it’s an opposition state and would go directly to its crony. “Adopting selective approach to end a scourge that cannot differentiate between political parties, race and religion is not good for our democracy.” The group urged all agencies of government, both federal, state or local government to synergise and work in tandem to get best result.